         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">Melbourne ¶ Christmas ¶ 1874. ¶  ¶ You being the author of a highly valuable pocket-volume on English or rather British plants, ¶  dear Dr Hooker, you must naturally be interested in any additions, th...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">74.12.25a</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To Joseph Hooker</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">RBG Kew, Kew correspondence, Australia, Mueller, 1871-81, f. 160.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">MS annotation: 'Ans. March 10th'. In this edition as J. Hooker to M, 75-03-10a.</p>
               </note>Melbourne</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">Christmas</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">1874.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>You being the author of a highly valuable pocket-volume on English or rather British plants,<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">J. Hooker (1870), in which <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Juncus%20capitatus">Juncus capitatus</name>
                     </seg> is mentioned (p. 392), but <seg style="font-style: italic; ">J. pygmaeus</seg> is not listed. However, in the second edition (1878) both are listed (p. 416). See J. Hooker to M, 10 March 1875.</p>
               </note> dear Dr Hooker, you must naturally be interested in any additions, that could likely be made. Allow me to mention then, that I always found with <name key="Juncus%20pygmaeus">Juncus pygmaeus</name> also <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">J. capitatus</hi>
               </seg>.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>In Trimens journal 2 or 3 years ago, I pointed out, that <name key="Chenolea%20hirsuta">Chenolea hirsuta</name> in its almost <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">glabrous</hi>
               </seg> form was almost sure to exist with <name key="Suaeda%20maritima">Suaeda maritima</name> on your coasts, and that by its tendency to a spiral twist of the upper stem it could often be recognized, without dissecting the fruit.<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">B73.06.01.</p>
               </note> A minute tuft of hair in the axils allows also the plant easily to be recognized. Could not one of your assistants search carefully through the Kew collections of <name key="Suaeda%20maritima">Suaeda maritima</name> for finding British specimens of the Chenolea</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>So it might also be done with <name key="Scirpus%20silvaticus">Scirpus silvaticus</name>.<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Scirpus sylvaticus?</seg>
                  </p>
               </note> Surely mixed with it is S. radicans? The setae of the two are very different, but who would suspect that when 2 plants, so similar in outward appearance grow together. The spikelets of S. radicans are always larger and generally <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">singly</hi>
               </seg>
               <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">dispersed</hi>
               </seg> but not so much clustered. I have found an other character, nowhere recorded: S. silvaticus has the branches of the panicle hairy-scabrous (like in my S. polystachyus), not smooth as in S. radicans.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I find, that S. fluviatilis (A. Gray) is here on many places, but perhaps only on Freshwater streams. May it not have been confounded in your islands &amp; elsewhere with S. maritimus.</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">Regardfully yr</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Ferd. von Mueller</p>
